  "doc_id": "37931",
  "text": "The typical non-caseating granulomatous lesions of sarcoidosis are usually found in the epineurium. Chronic necrotizing vasculitis in the absence of granulomas can be present in other cases of sarcoidosis. The inflammatory infiltration is mainly associated with axonal neuropathy; only rarely a predominant demyelinating pattern is seen [CITATION_1] . Again, combining nerve biopsy with muscle biopsy may increase the chance of detecting the pathognomonic lesions [CITATION_2] . Small fiber neuropathy is a frequent complication of sarcoidosis and can be diagnosed by skin biopsy [CITATION_3] .",
